erm conflicts and emergencies.\n\nThe happiness of your empire isn't something that is static. To begin with, dissatisfaction will naturally fluctuate a little on its own and differ from city to city. Next, random events such as natural disasters, eclipses or omens can cause large swings in mood, the negative effects of which can be mitigated with research. Furthermore, the authority of your leader may vary. Send him out to win victories and your people will be less inclined to rebel. Lose battles and your authority will decrease. If he dies in battle or old age, his successor will have a temporary penalty to authority. It\u2019s even worse if your leader dies without an heir. Messy power struggles after a king\u2019s death are common in history, so it\u2019s nice that the game reflects this with its mechanics.\n\nRebellions aren't easy to deal with. Nobles are more likely to rebel further away from your capital, and armies with too many peasants will join peasant rebellions. Creating and moving professional armies around takes time. Entire cities can defect to rebels. The AI isn't immune to infighting; It's satisfying to watch a large rival split in two.\n\nEdicts are handled cleverly too. You can order your nobles to keep horses to transform them from an infantry unit to a chariot unit, create a central bureaucracy, force peasants to use a new farming system for increased profits or recruit officers to reduce unhappiness in cities or grant a bonus to armies they lead. Passing one usually means angering nobles or farmers in the short term or permanently in addition to requiring gold per turn. Therefore they require a bit of thinking before using.\n\nPeople looking for total war style battles will be disappointed, but that doesn't mean the combat has no depth. Using various unit types, tactics and the terrain matters.\n\nSince it's difficult to control a huge number of cities on your own without rebellions, you'll need to create vassals and convice other factions to recognise you as Emperor to control the huge map of China.\n\nThis isn't a game where you paint the map your own color. Diplomacy is important and internal weakness is just as much of a threat as external factions.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505611563, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505716326, "recommendationid": "35011263", "language": "english", "votes_down": 3, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.523994", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1506920169, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 9, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 8388, "steamid": "76561198336205492", "num_games_owned": 6}, "votes_funny": 4, "votes_up": 51, "comment_count": "24", "review": "Cannot recommend the game in its current state.\nPurchased it soon after release hoping the developer would eventually hone the product into mixture of TW & Civ series set in ancient China.\nInstead of improving the game, however, the developer only made miniscule updates to the mechanics and mostly focused on Chinese translation and multiplayer functionality to increase potential audience.\nHopefully things turn around after it leave early access.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1504665936, "written_during_early_access": true, "timestamp_updated": 1504665936, "recommendationid": "34768448", "language": "english", "votes_down": 38, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.532832", "voted_up": false}, {"author": {"last_played": 1506844328, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 778, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 2214, "steamid": "76561198010383336", "num_games_owned": 58}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 10, "comment_count": 0, "review": "I don't usually write reviews, and was like most, sceptical until I gave it a fresh look.\n\nGotta say though, this is not as boring as Civ VI, sean bean voice was nice yet he always dies anyways and not much help anyways.\n\nWent in with a medium to steep learning curve expectation, simpl