rks and I think a lot of players get frustrated before they figure it out.  In general you use your upper classes to supress the peasants and the lower classes to keep the nobles in check, while your own professional soldiers and elites can be used against both.  Makes sense.  Once you understand this losing a city to revolt is very rare. So if you have a peasant revolt you will need to use armies made up more than 50% of nobles/professionals and ideally led by your king.  \n\nTo prevent your king constantly dying it is helpful to set their individual unit ai to \"withdraw\".\n\nHaving played several thousand turns too I will say the AI is better than average and quite good in most respects.  I feel AI can always be improved in games, which leads me to the other side of the coin.  There were a few times where say Qin declared war on me with 100% of their cities undefended and not a unit in sight on the hardest difficulty.  Even when it took several turns to approach they didn't make a single unit and I captured the strongest foritified cities in the game unopposed. Silly.  Then a huge wave of Qin came in from the north and got obliterated on their own fortresses.  Bad moves happen in war, if I would have attacked them I would just be taking advantage of their weakness and that is a smart move - but they declared war on me!  Those Qin should mass up on my borders first, especially if I am their chief rival for hegemony.\n\nThe game badly needs a harder difficulty than \"very hard.\"  Guys like me need more punishment, more collusion amongst the enemies.  Give them more gold and troops and make the ai more aggressive.\n\nI also feel like the base authority rating should be higher or that very small cities shouldn't consume a point until they grow to a certain size.  The map feels unpopulated until hundreds of turns pass and even then there is still open land just begging to be exploited but you cant beyond a small number or risk a big revolt.  So you just cede it and burn enemy cities.  More points could just be added to the base rate or to some techs.  It just leads to some weird semi arbitrary points where you almost need to disband pissant settlements in order to keep giant cities happy, and forces you to always keep your kings and heirs crusading on the front lines to increase their ratings.  The rating itself is fine as a system to prevent overexpansion but having the rating reset to when your king dies of old age is more annoying than fun especially when the number of cities the kingdom controls isn't that large.  This is CHINA.\n\nA large % of battles end up being sieges.  Nothing wrong with that, I actually really enjoy cracking a tough city and they should be difficult to take.  What I find immensely annoying though is sieging a city for 30 or 40 turns only to have a random guy come and take the city at the last second.  That is infuriating and it happens A LOT.  This leads to weird games were you try and time the last hit on the siege.  Obviously if I commit 3000 men and decades then a random guy comes and bypasses my siege lines and then takes the spoils that doesnt make any sense and is ridiculous. Without save scumming and trying to trial and error it you will lose the city, loot, resources, 1000s of men, time etc.\n\nI also think that many of the policies/edicts are awesome and also stupid at the same time.  Many of these don't seem balanced or worthwhile.  A king appointing a general reduces his authority?  Okay, maybe, but what happens when that loyal general goes on to conquer half the world for you and becomes famous and feared? Still reducing your authority. In a way it kind of make sense he might get delusions of grandeur or something and revolt but overall most generals throughout history have stayed loyal to their homeland and cause. Maybe they could add a loyalty stat, but I do like the way it is now, simplified to a city's loyalty.  The penalties especially in authority in regards to edicts  usually lead to never chosing certain options and that is unfun/unintended. It also leads to a lack of generals/personality characters until very late game.  I think that is one of this game's weaknesses, the characters feels all generic and lifeless when say a simple family tree or random trait system layered on top would add a lot in depth.  I want to feel like a king and I want to know who my vassals and enemies are. If I want to be Wei and choose 5 elite generals and war in all directions that is my perogitive - even it backfires and leads to revolts or a large cost, whatever, I at least want the option.   Even at max authority/characters it seems a bit light for the scale of all of China.\n\nI think they need a slightly better presentation for complex diplomacy.  Many games have a system where you click one nation and it reveals all the relations with coloured bars.  Would help organize a bit of the chaos in this chaotic ffa.\n\nIn the future I would like to see the player able to establish more historically accurate mods to their kingdom by undertaking customizable agricultural (irrigation/canal) improvements like the Zhengguo Canal and the Great wall of China.  They can add heavy fortifcations / castles that link together and maybe have levels since the QIn built a large defense against Chu even though it was nothing like the scale of the great wall.  They could even add river/canal diversions and dams etc to increase the usefulness of water/ship transport and similulate Qin's prepartion for their attack on the Yue.\n\nOverall Oriental Empires is excellent and should by purchased by those who love history, strategy, and quality games.  It is actually far better in my opinion that many AAA titles like Civilization.   The Warring states is basically a 100 way ffa of small kingdoms duking it out in the most chaotic and ignored period of history in the west.  While Rome was fielding 1000s, these kingdomss were raising 100,000s and rising and falling in never ending waves of battles and bloodshed!  Come get a piece!", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1506660698, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1506952211, "recommendationid": "35282592", "language": "english", "votes_down": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.505005", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505503601, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 9, "playtime_forever": 172, "steamid": "76561198097674101", "num_games_owned": 53}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 3, "comment_count": 0, "review": "nice little game. Sort of a mini Civ meets Total War. I got it on sale, but i would reccomend buying this when its not on sale as well if you're looking for something a little different to try.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1505784732, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1505784732, "recommendationid": "35056005", "language": "english", "votes_down": 1, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.505161", "voted_up": true}, {"author": {"last_played": 1505967616, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "num_reviews": 4, "playtime_forever": 324, "steamid": "76561198117653340", "num_games_owned": 77}, "votes_funny": 0, "votes_up": 9, "comment_count": "2", "review": "Looks cool on first play. Remeniscent of Civ games. But has no replay value and gets boring quick. \\\n\n-All tech trees are the same. \n-Army formations mean next to nothing. It's mostly RNG.\n-Combat is stupid, where the losing army always retreats and you never really win, but have to keep expensive units everywhere to keep them from raiding your farms because you can never kill them. It takes like 5 engagements to kill bandits, supposedly the easiest enemy in the game. But they can go anywhere so you need several groups of expensive soldiers scattered about just to keep them from destroying your farms.\n-You are supposed to expand fast, but if you expand too fast, you'll get more bandits to deal with. If you don't exp